<HEAD>Soldiers, Peasants Clash in Northwest Haiti</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers and peasants clashed in
the hamlet of Danti in northwest Haiti with a rural law officer
reported killed and many peasants wounded, radio stations in the
capital said Tuesday.
   The report coincided with a plea by Foreign Minister Gerard
LaTortue on Tuesday for international aid for this impoverished
Caribbean nation. He told a news conference at Puerto Rico's
Department of State, ``No democratic process can sustain itself if
it is not accompanied by economic development.''
   The United States suspended most of its aid to Haiti following
election violence last November.
   Section chief Leroy Ely was killed in Danti last Thursday,
touching off the clashes which reportedly continued until Monday.
   Section chiefs in Haiti are rural police officers with military
rank, responsible for supervising public works as well as
maintaining law and order. Under the 29-year Duvalier family
dictatorship, section chiefs exercised wide powers.
   Ely traveled to Danti to impose the authority of the capital
city of the section, Le Borgne. Peasants demanded their hamlet be
assigned to neighboring Gros Morne district and in subsequent
rioting, Ely was killed.
   Soldiers came to quell the unrest. Radio Lumiere, Radio
Metropole and Radio Haiti Inter reported that from Thursday to
Monday, Danti residents were beaten and arrested or forced to flee.
Their homes were pillaged and burned.
   Witnesses interviewed by Radio Metropole said many people were
wounded or forced to take flight. Radio Haiti Inter said 25
peasants were arrested.
   According to Radio Metropole, Danti is in a relatively fertile
zone and Le Borgne authorities did not want to lose it.
   Disputes over land have become common and violent in this arid,
mountainous and overpopulated nation that shares the island of
Hispaniola with the Dominican Republic.
   Last July, hundreds of peasants clashed with landowners and
among themselves over property in the northwest village of Jean
Rabel. Dozens were killed.
   In asking for foreign help, LaTortue said in San Juan, Puerto
Rico, that ``For us Haitians, economic development means ... food
and water for the great majority of the population, and health
services, education and housing.''
   The United States has been Haiti's biggest foreign aid donor,
contributing $103 million a year to the poorest nation in the
Western Hemisphere, with a population of 5.3 million.
   Most U.S. aid was suspended following cancellation of last
November's national elections because of violence, which the
then-ruling junta under Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy did little to curtail.
   France and Canada maintained their aid commitments to Haiti, but
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund have withheld
$40 million in loans.
   LaTortue, who spent 10 years in Puerto Rico as part of his
25-year exile during the Duvalier dictatorships, criticized U.S.
officials for blocking aid to Haiti following controversial
national elections last January.
   He asked Puerto Rico, a U.S. commonwealth, to make available
scholarships for Haitian students and do what it could to promote
Haiti's economic development.
   Dictator Francois Duvalier ruled Haiti since 1957. His son,
Jean-Claude, took over at his death but fled Feb. 7, 1986 during a
popular uprising. A president, Leslie Manigat, was chosen in
January.
</TEXT>
