<HEAD>Strike Paralyzes Capital; Radio Report: Duvalier Plans Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A protest strike over the return
from exile of two former officials linked to human rights abuses
under dictatorial regimes on Wednesday paralyzed this normally
bustling capital of 1 million people.
   Meanwhile, the independent Radio Haiti-Inter reported deposed
dictator Jean-Claude ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier had booked a flight to
Haiti for July 29 and that two of his former ministers were
expected to arrive Wednesday night.
   Duvalier has lived in exile in France since he was ousted in a
popular uprising in February 1986.
   The radio station gave no attribution for the report, which
could not be independently confirmed.
   The one-day protest strike was supported by political groups,
labor unions and many civic groups. Strike supporters expressed
concern that Duvalier supporters were attempting to make a comeback
in Haiti.
   Downtown shops, open-air markets and gas stations were closed
for the one-day protest, and no buses were running. Streets were
virtually deserted.
   Employers sent home the few assembly line workers who showed up
for work at the sprawling industrial park near the airport,
independent Radio Antilles reported. About 15,000 people are
employed there.
   Reports from Cap-Haitien and Gonaives, Haiti's second- and
third-largest cities, indicated widespread support for the strike
in the provinces. Most businesses were closed but buses were still
running.
   There were no reports of violence.
   Unity Assembly, a coalition of 12 political groups, called the
strike Tuesday after the government failed to comply with its
demand to arrest two former high-ranking officials, Roger Lafontant
and Williams Regala, who returned separately from exile last week.
   As interior and defense minister under ``Baby Doc'' Duvalier,
Lafontant reputedly headed the dreaded Tonton Macoutes paramilitary
force. Duvalier's ouster ended the 29-year dynasty founded by his
father, Francois ``Papa Doc,'' who died in 1971.
   Regala, a retired army major general, served as interior and
defense minister under two previous military regimes. He is widely
regarded as the mastermind of the election day massacre of Nov. 29,
1987, in which thugs supported by the army shot and hacked to death
at least 34 voters at polling stations.
   Lafontant had been living in self-imposed exile in the
neighboring Dominican Republic the past 4{ years.
   Regala fled to the United States in March when military ruler
Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril was forced into exile by a popular uprising.
   Their return to Haiti heightened fears of an organized attempt
to disrupt general elections scheduled for Nov. 4.
   Unity Assembly declared in a statement that Lafontant and Regala
``at large are ill omens of growing insecurity and a slap in the
face of justice.''
   In San Juan, Puerto Rico, Paul Laortue, a Senate candidate in
the aborted 1987 elections, said the return of Lafontant and Regala
was a ``very serious test by the Duvalierist sector to find out if
they can make a comeback.''
   ``If these two guys can stay in Haiti, that means that before
the end of the year Jean-Claude Duvalier could attempt to come
back. ... I don't know if he would dare, but it would be viable,''
said Latortue, who now teaches at the University of Puerto Rico.
   The Unity Assembly coalition had given civilian President Ertha
Pascal-Trouillot until noon Tuesday to arrest Lafontant and Regala.
   Mrs. Pascal-Trouillot, who was appointed president to succeed
Avril, made no public statement in response to the protest.
   Her silence underscored a long-standing rift between the
president and the 19-member Council of State, which was appointed
to govern alongside her in a caretaker civilian government.
   In a statement Monday, the Council of State said Lafontant and
Regala had been widely accused of ``repeated human-rights
violations and illicit enrichment.''
   The council said their return from exile was ``due to the policy
of the present executive (Mrs. Pascal-Trouillot), which hasn't
managed to set the legal process in motion.''
   An arrest warrant for Lafontant, issued Saturday by government
prosecutor Bayard Vincent, was not served. But the police chief,
Col. Jean-Claude Duperval, said it would be, independent Tele-Haiti
reported Tuesday. A second warrant was issued Tuesday morning.
</TEXT>
