<LEADPARA>  Amid reports of random attacks by soldiers, a high-level delegation from the
Organization of American States was expected to arrive here today to demand
that leaders of Monday's military coup step aside and restore President
Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power.;   Brig. Gen. Raoul Cedras, the coup leader,
said in a radio address that he would receive the OAS mission. But he
defiantly vowed not to step aside.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DIPLOMATS SEEK RESIGNATION OF HAITIAN COUP'S
LEADERS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Western diplomats in Haiti estimated that as many as 350 civilians had died
in the insurrection.;   Radio Lumiere, one of several independent radio
stations that has managed to periodically broadcast from inside Haiti, said 30
to 40 supporters of Aristide were massacred Wednesday afternoon in a
Port-au-Prince slum.;   On the eve of the OAS delegation's arrival, the
normally teeming capital of 1 million was a virtual ghost town Thursday for
the fourth straight working day.;   Businesses closed; A few people wandered
the streets and soldiers stopped cars at checkpoints, searching for weapons.
Businesses were shut down, either out of fear or as part of a protest boycott
against Aristide's ouster.;   The airport remained closed to all but a few
charter flights of diplomats and journalists. There was no indication of when
commercial air service would be restored or commercial activity resumed.;   On
the fourth day since the army's takeover, diplomats on Thursday depicted
Cedras as being largely the captive of the ordinary soldiers who were
patrolling streets, commandeering cars, and threatening citizens.;   Diplomats
said there was no coherent chain of command in the country to rein in the
soldiers who were set against Aristide's return.;   In Washington, where he
lobbied for support on Capitol Hill before flying to New York to seek help
from the U.N. Security Council, Aristide referred to the coup leaders as "a
small gang trying to kill democracy." He was to meet with President Bush at
the White House this morning.;   Ready for evacuation; Meanwhile, hundreds of
U.S. troops remained poised to evacuate thousands of Americans if the
situation worsens in this impoverished Caribbean nation. At least 8,000
Americans have registered with the U.S. Embassy. Thousands more -- many of
them missionaries -- are believed to be scattered throughout countryside.;  
For the time being, the United States appeared to be ruling out military force
in favor of giving diplomatic pressure a chance to restore the 38-year-old
Aristide to the presidency.;   Secretary of State James Baker and other
diplomats attending an emergency 10-hour meeting late Wednesday of the
34-nation OAS in Washington hinted that force might be used if Aristide was
not reinstated. But the Bush administration played down that possibility on
Thursday.;   "We have absolutely no interest in using U.S. forces to in any
way interfere with the internal situation in Haiti," Pentagon spokesman Pete
Williams said.;    OAS resolution; In its emergency session, the OAS adopted
an 11-point resolution urging its members to diplomatically and economically
isolate Haiti. Many nations, including the United States, have suspended all
aid to Haiti, one of the world's poorest countries.;   The resolution stopped
short of endorsing military action but said "all additional measures" would be
taken if peaceful efforts fail to restore Aristide.;   In Washington, the
Venezuelan Embassy confirmed a report that its army had been placed on alert
Thursday and told to prepare for a multinational military operation if
diplomatic efforts fail.  </TEXT>
