<HEAD>Soldiers Say They're On The Side of the Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Rank-and-file soldiers who helped
oust Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy and more than 50 of his military
commanders promised Monday to protect the rights of the poor.
   ``We are not only defending the enlisted men, we are speaking
for all the poor people,'' an unidentified soldier was quoted as
telling Radio Haiti Inter at army general headquarters in downtown
Port-au-Prince.
   ``People have the right to demonstrate, to express what's in
their hearts, as long as they do it peacefully,'' he said, adding
that soldiers would guarantee the safety of demonstrators.
   Another soldier said the 50 or more superior officers who have
been ousted by their troops since the Sept. 17 uprising against
Namphy will not be allowed to return to the army.
   ``We won't allow it,'' he said, adding that soldiers are still
demanding the ouster of more officers because of their unpopularity
or ties to the 29-year Duvalier family dictatorship.
   The soldiers were not identified by the radio station.
   Members of Namphy's Presidential Guard, led by 27-year-old Sgt.
Joseph Heubreux, said they ousted Namphy because they were
``sickened'' by his alleged collusion with thugs of the Duvalier
regime who massacred 13 parishioners and wounded more than 77
others people during a Mass on Sept. 11.
   The soldiers appointed Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril as the new
president.
   Also Monday, soldiers ordered the dismissal of the director of
the general post office, Jean Malette, after employees went on
strike demanding his ouster. Malette was replaced by Jean-Claude
Jean-Jacques, a managerial level employee.
   Employees of state agencies, following the example of Haiti's
7,000 soldiers, have ousted the unpopular directors of the state
flour mill, telephone company and water authority.
   Jacques Armand Charles, the new state prosecutor, was sworn in
Monday at the Palace of Justice, replacing Namphy-appointee
Mireille Zamor Pluviose.
   Meanwhile, Haiti Inter and Radio Metropole reported Monday that
former members of the Tonton Macoutes, the private army under the
Duvalier regime, killed three peasants who were protesting their
presence in Verrette, a village 60 miles north of the capital.
   The alleged Tonton Macoutes were accompanied by local police
Chief Dumarsais Charles, the radio stations reported.
   The regime begun by dictator Francois ``Papa Doc'' Duvalier in
1957 ended when his son, Jean-Claude, fled into exile in February
1986. Namphy took over as head of a three-man junta until Leslie
Manigat was elected president last January in balloting widely
thought to be fraudulent.
   Namphy ousted Manigat in a coup last June.
</TEXT>
